<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870324-0003 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 03/24/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   AMERICAN EXPRESS SAID its board approved an initial stock offering of at least 18% in its Shearson Lehman securities unit. The offering would have a value of $600 million to $700 million. The board also approved the sale of a 13% Shearson stake to Nippon Life of Japan.    ---   Merrill Lynch's Canadian unit is holding talks to acquire Burns Fry Corp., the parent of one of Canada's largest securities firms, sources said. Terms of the bid aren't known.    ---   The dollar plunged to a post-World War II low against the Japanese yen. The drop was triggered by Treasury Secretary Baker's comment that the U.S. doesn't have a target for the dollar's value. Bond prices slumped in reaction to the dollar's slide.    ---   Blue-chip stocks surged to new highs in heavy trading, though other sectors weren't as strong. The Dow Jones industrials closed up 30.26 points, at a record 2363.78. Stock-index futures also rose as Friday's rally brought a flood of buy orders.    ---   The Swiss government froze bank accounts of individuals and companies named in an SEC insider-trading case involving a former Merrill Lynch executive. The move further indicated that the U.S. plans criminal proceedings against the defendants.    ---   IBM is speeding up by two months the deliveries of its new midrange computers because it has been losing market share to Digital Equipment. Meanwhile, Hewlett-Packard said it began shipping test models of its new business minicomputer.    ---   Japan moved to head off expected U.S. trade sanctions against Japanese microchip producers. Tokyo said it told makers to cut output of certain chips, but U.S. officials were skeptical that it would forestall sanctions.    ---   Harper andamp; Row said it is holding talks with a &quot;considerable number&quot; of U.S. and foreign firms about a possible restructuring or acquisition. The publishing company already has received two takeover bids.    ---   Financial Corp. of America said it isn't holding talks with anyone about a possible sale of the thrift holding company. But it said it is willing to talk to prospective buyers.    ---   Former JWT Group executive Joseph O'Donnell today will be named head of William Esty Co., a unit of Saatchi andamp; Saatchi.    ---   Fannie Mae is starting a program to buy 10- and 20-year mortgages, a move that could increase the availability of those loans, officials said. Fannie Mae usually buys home loans with 15- or 30-year maturities.    ---   R.D. Smith andamp; Co. said it has been subpoenaed in the government's investigation of alleged manipulation of Fireman's Fund stock last year.    ---   Jefferies Group said the SEC staff accepted the firm's accounting of a $5 million loss from a 1986 transaction.    ---   The U.S. withdrew a proposed compromise on voting changes at the Inter-American Development Bank. A dispute over the changes is keeping the bank from boosting its lending.    ---   Investor Martin Sosnoff said he has held talks with Pratt Hotel and Southmark about a possible joint venture to acquire Caesars World.    ---   Wickes Cos. plans to sell its 85% stake in its British home improvement unit to a management group for about $155 million.    ---   American Motors said its 1986 financial results were qualified because of a $64 million arbitration award against a former AMC unit.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 189,070,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2363.78, up 30.26; transportation 947.55, off 1.34; utilities 221.56, up 1.44.    Bonds: Dow Jones 20 bonds 94.71, off 0.14.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 114.57, up 0.85; spot </TEXT></DOC>